# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: recommender-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] The cold start problem is a well known and well researched problem for recommender systems.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Recommender systems form a specific type of information filtering (IF) technique that attempts to present information items (e-commerce, films, music, books, news, images, web pages) that are likely of interest to the user.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Typically, a recommender system compares the user's profile to some reference characteristics.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] These characteristics may be related to item characteristics (content-based filtering) or the user's social environment and past behavior (collaborative filtering).
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Depending on the system, the user can be associated to various kinds of interactions: ratings, bookmarks, purchases, likes, number of page visits etc.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] The new community problem, or systemic bootstrapping, refers to the startup of the system, when virtually no information the recommender can rely upon is present.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] This case presents the disadvantages of both the New user and the New item case, as all items and users are new.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Due to this some of the techniques developed to deal with those two cases are not applicable to the system bootstrapping.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] The item cold-start problem refers to when items added to the catalogue have either none or very little interactions.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] This constitutes a problem mainly for collaborative filtering algorithms due to the fact that they rely on the item's interactions to make recommendations.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] If no interactions are available then a pure collaborative algorithm cannot recommend the item.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] In case only a few interactions are available, although a collaborative algorithm will be able to recommend it, the quality of those recommendations will be poor.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] This raises another issue, which is not anymore related to new items, but rather to *unpopular items*.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] In some cases (e.g. movie recommendations) it might happen that a handful of items receive an extremely high number of interactions, while most of the items only receive a fraction of them.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] This is referred to as **popularity bias**.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] In the context of cold-start items the popularity bias is important because it might happen that many items, even if they have been in the catalogue for months, received only a few interactions.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] This creates a negative loop in which unpopular items will be poorly recommended, therefore will receive much less visibility than popular ones, and will struggle to receive interactions.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] While it is expected that some items will be less popular than others, this issue specifically refers to the fact that the recommender has not enough collaborative information to recommend them in a meaningful and reliable way.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Content-based filtering algorithms, on the other hand, are in theory much less prone to the new item problem.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Since content based recommenders choose which items to recommend based on the feature the items possess, even if no interaction for a new item exist, still its features will allow for a recommendation to be made.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] This of course assumes that a new item will be already described by its attributes, which is not always the case.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Consider the case of so-called *editorial* features (e.g. director, cast, title, year), those are always known when the item, in this case movie, is added to the catalogue.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] However, other kinds of attributes might not be e.g. features extracted from user reviews and tags.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Content-based algorithms relying on user provided features suffer from the cold-start item problem as well, since for new items if no (or very few) interactions exist, also no (or very few) user reviews and tags will be available.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] The new user case refers to when a new user enrolls in the system and for a certain period of time the recommender has to provide recommendation without relying on the user's past interactions, since none has occurred yet.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] The main strategy in dealing with new users is to ask them to provide some preferences to build an initial user profile.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] A threshold has to be found between the length of the user registration process, which if too long might induce too many users to abandon it, and the amount of initial data required for the recommender to work properly.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Similarly to the new items case, not all recommender algorithms are affected in the same way.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Item-item recommenders will be affected as they rely on user profile to weight how relevant other user's preferences are.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Collaborative filtering algorithms are the most affected as without interactions no inference can be made about the user's preferences.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] User-user recommender algorithms behave slightly differently.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] A user-user content based algorithm will rely on user's features (e.g. age, gender, country) to find similar users and recommend the items they interacted with in a positive way, therefore being robust to the new user case.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Note that all these information is acquired during the registration process, either by asking the user to input the data himself, or by leveraging data already available e.g. in his social media accounts.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Due to the high number of recommender algorithms available as well as system type and characteristics, many strategies to mitigate the cold-start problem have been developed.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] The main approach is to rely on hybrid recommenders, in order to mitigate the disadvantages of one category or model by combining it with another.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] All three categories of cold-start (new community, new item, and new user) have in common the lack of user interactions and presents some commonalities in the strategies available to address them.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] A common strategy when dealing with new items is to couple a collaborative filtering recommender, for warm items, with a content-based filtering recommender, for cold-items.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] While the two algorithms can be combined in different ways, the main drawback of this method is related to the poor recommendation quality often exhibited by content-based recommenders in scenarios where it is difficult to provide a comprehensive description of the item characteristics.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] In case of new users, if no demographic feature is present or their quality is too poor, a common strategy is to offer them non-personalized recommendations.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] This means that they could be recommended simply the most popular items either globally or for their specific geographical region or language.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] One of the available options when dealing with cold users or items is to rapidly acquire some preference data.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] There are various ways to do that depending on the amount of information required.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] These techniques are called preference elicitation strategies.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] This may be done either explicitly (by querying the user) or implicitly (by observing the user's behaviour).
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] In both cases, the cold start problem would imply that the user has to dedicate an amount of effort using the system in its 'dumb' state – contributing to the construction of their user profile – before the system can start providing any intelligent recommendations.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] For example MovieLens, a web-based recommender system for movies, asks the user to rate some movies as a part of the registration.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] While preference elicitation strategy are a simple and effective way to deal with new users, the additional requirements during the registration will make the process more time-consuming for the user.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Moreover, the quality of the obtained preferences might not be ideal as the user could rate items they had seen months or years ago or the provided ratings could be almost random if the user provided them without paying attention just to complete the registration quickly.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] The construction of the user's profile may also be automated by integrating information from other user activities, such as browsing histories or social media platforms.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] If, for example, a user has been reading information about a particular music artist from a media portal, then the associated recommender system would automatically propose that artist's releases when the user visits the music store.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] A variation of the previous approach is to automatically assign ratings to new items, based on the ratings assigned by the community to other similar items.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Item similarity would be determined according to the items' content-based characteristics.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] It is also possible to create initial profile of a user based on the personality characteristics of the user and use such profile to generate personalized recommendation.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Personality characteristics of the user can be identified using a personality model such as five factor model (FFM).
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Another of the possible techniques is to apply active learning (machine learning).
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] The main goal of active learning is to guide the user in the preference elicitation process in order to ask him to rate only the items that for the recommender point of view will be the most informative ones.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] This is done by analysing the available data and estimating the usefulness of the data points (e.g., ratings, interactions).
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] As an example, say that we want to build two clusters from a certain cloud of points.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] As soon as we have identified two points each belonging to a different cluster, which is the next most informative point?
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] If we take a point close to one we already know we can expect that it will likely belong to the same cluster.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] If we choose a point which is in between the two clusters, knowing which cluster it belongs to will help us in finding where the boundary is, allowing to classify many other points with just a few observations.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] The cold start problem is also exhibited by interface agents.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Since such an agent typically learns the user's preferences implicitly by observing patterns in the user's behaviour – "watching over the shoulder" – it would take time before the agent may perform any adaptations personalised to the user.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Even then, its assistance would be limited to activities which it has formerly observed the user engaging in.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] The cold start problem may be overcome by introducing an element of collaboration amongst agents assisting various users.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] This way, novel situations may be handled by requesting other agents to share what they have already learnt from their respective users.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] In recent years more advanced strategies have been proposed, they all rely on machine learning and attempt to merge the content and collaborative information in a single model.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] One example of this approaches is called *attribute to feature mapping* which is tailored to matrix factorization algorithms.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] A matrix factorization model represents the user-item interactions as the product of two rectangular matrices whose content is learned using the known interactions via machine learning.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Each user will be associated to a row of the first matrix and each item with a column of the second matrix.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] The row or column associated to a specific user or item is called *latent factors*.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] When a new item is added it has no associated latent factors and the lack of interactions does not allow to learn them, as it was done with other items.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] If each item is associated to some features (e.g. author, year, publisher, actors) it is possible to define an embedding function, which given the item features estimates the corresponding item latent factors.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] The embedding function can be designed in many ways and it is trained with the data already available from warm items.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Alternatively, one could apply a group-specific method.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] A group-specific method further decomposes each latent factor into two additive parts: One part corresponds to each item (and/or each user), while the other part is shared among items within each item group (e.g., a group of movies could be movies of the same genre).
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Then once a new item arrives, we can assign a group label to it, and approximates its latent factor by the group-specific part (of the corresponding item group).
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Therefore, although the individual part of the new item is not available, the group-specific part provides an immediate and effective solution.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] The same applies for a new user, as if some information is available for them (e.g. age, nationality, gender) then his/her latent factors can be estimated via an embedding function or a group-specific latent factor.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Another recent approach which bears similarities with feature mapping is building a hybrid content-based filtering recommender in which features, either of the items or of the users, are weighted according to the user's perception of importance.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] In order to identify a movie that the user could like, different attributes (e.g. which are the actors, director, country, title) will have different importance.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] As an example consider the James Bond movie series, the main actor changed many times during the years, while some did not, like Lois Maxwell.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Therefore, her presence will probably be a better identifier of that kind of movie than the presence of one of the various main actors.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Although various techniques exist to apply feature weighting to user or item features in recommender systems, most of them are from the information retrieval domain like tf–idf, Okapi BM25, only a few have been developed specifically for recommenders.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Hybrid feature weighting techniques in particular are tailored for the recommender system domain.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Some of them learn feature weight by exploiting directly the user's interactions with items, like FBSM.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Others rely on an intermediate collaborative model trained on warm items and attempt to learn the content feature weights which will better approximate the collaborative model.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Many of the hybrid methods can be considered special cases of factorization machines.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] The above methods rely on affiliated information from users or items.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] It is shown that various recommendation models benefit from this strategy.
[src:recommender-systems/cold-start-recommender-systems] Differentiating regularization weights can be integrated with the other cold start mitigating strategies.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] In the newer, narrower sense, collaborative filtering is a method of making automatic predictions (filtering) about a user's interests by utilizing preferences or taste information collected from many users (collaborating).
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] This approach assumes that if persons *A* and *B* share similar opinions on one issue, they are more likely to agree on other issues compared to a random pairing of *A* with another person.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] For instance, a collaborative filtering system for television programming could predict which shows a user might enjoy based on a limited list of the user's tastes (likes or dislikes).
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] These predictions are specific to the user, but use information gleaned from many users.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] This differs from the simpler approach of giving an average (non-specific) score for each item of interest, for example based on its number of votes.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] In the more general sense, collaborative filtering is the process of filtering information or patterns using techniques involving collaboration among multiple agents, viewpoints, data sources, etc.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Applications of collaborative filtering typically involve very large data sets.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] This article focuses on collaborative filtering for user data, but some of the methods also apply to other major applications.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The growth of the Internet has made it much more difficult to effectively extract useful information from all the available online information.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The overwhelming amount of data necessitates mechanisms for efficient information filtering.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Collaborative filtering is one of the techniques used for dealing with this problem.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The motivation for collaborative filtering comes from the idea that people often get the best recommendations from someone with tastes similar to themselves.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Collaborative filtering encompasses techniques for matching people with similar interests and making recommendations on this basis.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Collaborative filtering algorithms often require (1) users' active participation, (2) an easy way to represent users' interests, and (3) algorithms that are able to match people with similar interests.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The system matches this user's ratings against other users' and finds the people with most "similar" tastes.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] A key problem of collaborative filtering is how to combine and weight the preferences of user neighbors.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Sometimes, users can immediately rate the recommended items.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] As a result, the system gains an increasingly accurate representation of user preferences over time.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] This falls under the category of user-based collaborative filtering.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] A specific application of this is the user-based Nearest Neighbor algorithm.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] See, for example, the Slope One item-based collaborative filtering family.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Another form of collaborative filtering can be based on implicit observations of normal user behavior (as opposed to the artificial behavior imposed by a rating task).
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] These systems observe what a user has done together with what all users have done (what music they have listened to, what items they have bought) and use that data to predict the user's behavior in the future, or to predict how a user might like to behave given the chance.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] These predictions then have to be filtered through business logic to determine how they might affect the actions of a business system.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] For example, it is not useful to offer to sell somebody a particular album of music if they already have demonstrated that they own that music.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Relying on a scoring or rating system which is averaged across all users ignores specific demands of a user, and is particularly poor in tasks where there is large variation in interest (as in the recommendation of music).
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] However, there are other methods to combat information explosion, such as web search and data clustering.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The memory-based approach uses user rating data to compute the similarity between users or items.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Typical examples of this approach are neighbourhood-based CF and item-based/user-based top-N recommendations.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] where *U* denotes the set of top *N* users that are most similar to user *u* who rated item *i*.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] where ${\bar {r_{u}}}$ is the average rating of user *u* for all the items rated by *u*.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The neighborhood-based algorithm calculates the similarity between two users or items, and produces a prediction for the user by taking the weighted average of all the ratings.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Similarity computation between items or users is an important part of this approach.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Multiple measures, such as Pearson correlation and vector cosine based similarity are used for this.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] where Ixy is the set of items rated by both user *x* and user *y*.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The user based top-N recommendation algorithm uses a similarity-based vector model to identify the *k* most similar users to an active user.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] After the *k* most similar users are found, their corresponding user-item matrices are aggregated to identify the set of items to be recommended.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] A popular method to find the similar users is the Locality-sensitive hashing, which implements the nearest neighbor mechanism in linear time.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The advantages with this approach include: the explainability of the results, which is an important aspect of recommendation systems; easy creation and use; easy facilitation of new data; content-independence of the items being recommended; good scaling with co-rated items.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] There are also several disadvantages of this approach.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Its performance decreases when data is sparse, which is common for web-related items.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] This hinders the scalability of this approach and creates problems with large datasets.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Although it can efficiently handle new users because it relies on a data structure, adding new items becomes more complicated because that representation usually relies on a specific vector space.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Adding new items requires inclusion of the new item and the re-insertion of all the elements in the structure.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] An alternative to memory-based methods is to learn models to predict users' rating of unrated items.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Model-based CF algorithms include Bayesian networks, clustering models, latent semantic models such as singular value decomposition, probabilistic latent semantic analysis, multiple multiplicative factor, latent Dirichlet allocation and Markov decision process-based models.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Through this approach, dimensionality reduction methods are mostly used for improving robustness and accuracy of memory-based methods.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Specifically, methods like singular value decomposition, principal component analysis, known as latent factor models, compress a user-item matrix into a low-dimensional representation in terms of latent factors.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] This transforms the large matrix that contains many missing values, into a much smaller matrix.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] A compressed matrix can be used to find neighbors of a user or item as per the previous section.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Compression has two advantages in large, sparse data: it is more accurate and scales better.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] A number of applications combine the memory-based and the model-based CF algorithms.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] These overcome the limitations of native CF approaches and improve prediction performance.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Importantly, they overcome the CF problems such as sparsity and loss of information.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] However, they have increased complexity and are expensive to implement.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Usually most commercial recommender systems are hybrid, for example, the Google news recommender system.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] In recent years, many neural and deep-learning techniques have been proposed for collaborative filtering.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Some generalize traditional matrix factorization algorithms via a non-linear neural architecture, or leverage new model types like Variational Autoencoders.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Deep learning has been applied to many scenarios (context-aware, sequence-aware, social tagging etc.).
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] However, deep learning effectiveness for collaborative recommendation has been questioned.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] A systematic analysis of publications using deep learning or neural methods to the top-k recommendation problem, published in top conferences (SIGIR, KDD, WWW, RecSys), found that, on average, less than 40% of articles are reproducible, and only 14% in some conferences.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Overall, the study identifies 18 articles, only 7 of them could be reproduced and 6 could be outperformed by older and simpler properly tuned baselines.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The article highlights potential problems in today's research scholarship and calls for improved scientific practices.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Similar issues have been spotted by others and also in sequence-aware recommender systems.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Many recommender systems simply ignore other contextual information existing alongside user's rating in providing item recommendation.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] However, by pervasive availability of contextual information such as time, location, social information, and type of the device that user is using, it is becoming more important than ever for a successful recommender system to provide a context-sensitive recommendation.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] According to Charu Aggrawal, "Context-sensitive recommender systems tailor their recommendations to additional information that defines the specific situation under which recommendations are made.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Taking contextual information into consideration, we will have additional dimension to the existing user-item rating matrix.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] As an instance, assume a music recommender system which provides different recommendations in corresponding to time of the day.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] In this case, it is possible a user have different preferences for a music in different time of a day.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Thus, instead of using user-item matrix, we may use tensor of order 3 (or higher for considering other contexts) to represent context-sensitive users' preferences.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] In order to take advantage of collaborative filtering and particularly neighborhood-based methods, approaches can be extended from a two-dimensional rating matrix into a tensor of higher order.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] For this purpose, the approach is to find the most similar/like-minded users to a target user; one can extract and compute similarity of slices (e.g. item-time matrix) corresponding to each user.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Unlike the context-insensitive case for which similarity of two rating vectors are calculated, in the context-aware approaches, the similarity of rating matrices corresponding to each user is calculated by using Pearson coefficients.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] After the most like-minded users are found, their corresponding ratings are aggregated to identify the set of items to be recommended to the target user.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The most important disadvantage of taking context into recommendation model is to be able to deal with larger dataset that contains much more missing values in comparison to user-item rating matrix.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Therefore, similar to matrix factorization methods, tensor factorization techniques can be used to reduce dimensionality of original data before using any neighborhood-based methods.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Unlike the traditional model of mainstream media, in which there are few editors who set guidelines, collaboratively filtered social media can have a very large number of editors, and content improves as the number of participants increases.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Services like Reddit, YouTube, and Last.fm are typical examples of collaborative filtering based media.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] One scenario of collaborative filtering application is to recommend interesting or popular information as judged by the community.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] As a typical example, stories appear in the front page of Reddit as they are "voted up" (rated positively) by the community.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] As the community becomes larger and more diverse, the promoted stories can better reflect the average interest of the community members.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Wikipedia is another application of collaborative filtering.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Volunteers contribute to the encyclopedia by filtering out facts from falsehoods.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Another aspect of collaborative filtering systems is the ability to generate more personalized recommendations by analyzing information from the past activity of a specific user, or the history of other users deemed to be of similar taste to a given user.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] These resources are used as user profiling and helps the site recommend content on a user-by-user basis.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The more a given user makes use of the system, the better the recommendations become, as the system gains data to improve its model of that user.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] A collaborative filtering system does not necessarily succeed in automatically matching content to one's preferences.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Unless the platform achieves unusually good diversity and independence of opinions, one point of view will always dominate another in a particular community.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] As in the personalized recommendation scenario, the introduction of new users or new items can cause the cold start problem, as there will be insufficient data on these new entries for the collaborative filtering to work accurately.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] In order to make appropriate recommendations for a new user, the system must first learn the user's preferences by analysing past voting or rating activities.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The collaborative filtering system requires a substantial number of users to rate a new item before that item can be recommended.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] In practice, many commercial recommender systems are based on large datasets.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] As a result, the user-item matrix used for collaborative filtering could be extremely large and sparse, which brings about challenges in the performance of the recommendation.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] One typical problem caused by the data sparsity is the cold start problem.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] As collaborative filtering methods recommend items based on users' past preferences, new users will need to rate a sufficient number of items to enable the system to capture their preferences accurately and thus provides reliable recommendations.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Similarly, new items also have the same problem.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] When new items are added to the system, they need to be rated by a substantial number of users before they could be recommended to users who have similar tastes to the ones who rated them.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The new item problem does not affect content-based recommendations, because the recommendation of an item is based on its discrete set of descriptive qualities rather than its ratings.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] As the numbers of users and items grow, traditional CF algorithms will suffer serious scalability problems.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] For example, with tens of millions of customers $O(M)$ and millions of items $O(N)$ , a CF algorithm with the complexity of n is already too large.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] As well, many systems need to react immediately to online requirements and make recommendations for all users regardless of their millions of users, with most computations happening in very large memory machines.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Synonyms refers to the tendency of a number of the same or very similar items to have different names or entries.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Most recommender systems are unable to discover this latent association and thus treat these products differently.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] For example, the seemingly different items "children's movie" and "children's film" are actually referring to the same item.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Indeed, the degree of variability in descriptive term usage is greater than commonly suspected.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The prevalence of synonyms decreases the recommendation performance of CF systems.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Topic Modeling (like the Latent Dirichlet Allocation technique) could solve this by grouping different words belonging to the same topic.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Gray sheep refers to the users whose opinions do not consistently agree or disagree with any group of people and thus do not benefit from collaborative filtering.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Black sheep are a group whose idiosyncratic tastes make recommendations nearly impossible.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Although this is a failure of the recommender system, non-electronic recommenders also have great problems in these cases, so having black sheep is an acceptable failure.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] In a recommendation system where everyone can give the ratings, people may give many positive ratings for their own items and negative ratings for their competitors'.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] It is often necessary for the collaborative filtering systems to introduce precautions to discourage such manipulations.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Collaborative filters are expected to increase diversity because they help us discover new products.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Some algorithms, however, may unintentionally do the opposite.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Because collaborative filters recommend products based on past sales or ratings, they cannot usually recommend products with limited historical data.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] This can create a rich-get-richer effect for popular products, akin to positive feedback.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] This bias toward popularity can prevent what are otherwise better consumer-product matches.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] A Wharton study details this phenomenon along with several ideas that may promote diversity and the "long tail." Several collaborative filtering algorithms have been developed to promote diversity and the "long tail" by recommending novel, unexpected, and serendipitous items.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] User-item matrix is a basic foundation of traditional collaborative filtering techniques, and it suffers from data sparsity problem (i.e. cold start).
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] As a consequence, except for user-item matrix, researchers are trying to gather more auxiliary information to help boost recommendation performance and develop personalized recommender systems.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Generally, there are two popular auxiliary information: attribute information and interaction information.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Attribute information describes a user's or an item's properties.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] For example, user attribute might include general profile (e.g. gender and age) and social contacts (e.g. followers or friends in social networks); Item attribute means properties like category, brand or content.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] In addition, interaction information refers to the implicit data showing how users interplay with the item.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Widely used interaction information contains tags, comments or reviews and browsing history etc.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Auxiliary information plays a significant role in a variety of aspects.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] Explicit social links, as a reliable representative of trust or friendship, is always employed in similarity calculation to find similar persons who share interest with the target user.
[src:recommender-systems/collaborative-filtering] The interaction-associated information – tags – is taken as a third dimension (in addition to user and item) in advanced collaborative filtering to construct a 3-dimensional tensor structure for exploration of recommendation.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] In data analysis, **cosine similarity** is a measure of similarity between two non-zero vectors defined in an inner product space.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity is the cosine of the angle between the vectors; that is, it is the dot product of the vectors divided by the product of their lengths.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] It follows that the cosine similarity does not depend on the magnitudes of the vectors, but only on their angle.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] The cosine similarity always belongs to the interval $[-1,+1].$ For example, two proportional vectors have a cosine similarity of +1, two orthogonal vectors have a similarity of 0, and two opposite vectors have a similarity of −1.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] In some contexts, the component values of the vectors cannot be negative, in which case the cosine similarity is bounded in $[0,1]$ .
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] For example, in information retrieval and text mining, each word is assigned a different coordinate and a document is represented by the vector of the numbers of occurrences of each word in the document.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity then gives a useful measure of how similar two documents are likely to be, in terms of their subject matter, and independently of the length of the documents.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] The technique is also used to measure cohesion within clusters in the field of data mining.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] One advantage of cosine similarity is its low complexity, especially for sparse vectors: only the non-zero coordinates need to be considered.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] Other names for cosine similarity include **Orchini similarity** and **Tucker coefficient of congruence**; the **Otsuka–Ochiai similarity** (see below) is cosine similarity applied to binary data.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] where $A_{i}$ and $B_{i}$ are the i th components of vectors $\mathbf {A}$ and $\mathbf {B}$ , respectively.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] The resulting similarity ranges from −1 meaning exactly opposite, to +1 meaning exactly the same, with 0 indicating orthogonality (no correlation), while in-between values indicate intermediate similarity or dissimilarity.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] For text matching, the attribute vectors *A* and *B* are usually the term frequency vectors of the documents.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity can be seen as a method of normalizing document length during comparison.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] In the case of information retrieval, the cosine similarity of two documents will range from $0\to 1$ , since the term frequencies cannot be negative.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] This remains true when using TF-IDF weights.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] The angle between two term frequency vectors cannot be greater than 90°.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] If the attribute vectors are normalized by subtracting the vector means (e.g., $A-{\bar {A}}$ ), the measure is called the centered cosine similarity and is equivalent to the Pearson correlation coefficient.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] By virtue of being proportional to squared Euclidean distance, the cosine distance is not a true distance metric; it does not exhibit the triangle inequality property — or, more formally, the Schwarz inequality — and it violates the coincidence axiom.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] To repair the triangle inequality property while maintaining the same ordering, one can convert to Euclidean distance ${\textstyle {\sqrt {2(1-S_{C}(A,B))}}}$ or angular distance *θ* = arccos(*S**C*(*A*, *B*)).
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] Alternatively, the triangular inequality that does work for angular distances can be expressed directly in terms of the cosines; see below.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] The normalized angle, referred to as **angular distance**, between any two vectors A and B is a formal distance metric and can be calculated from the cosine similarity.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] The complement of the angular distance metric can then be used to define **angular similarity** function bounded between 0 and 1, inclusive.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] Unfortunately, computing the inverse cosine (arccos) function is slow, making the use of the angular distance more computationally expensive than using the more common (but not metric) cosine distance above.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] Another effective proxy for cosine distance can be obtained by $L_{2}$ normalisation of the vectors, followed by the application of normal Euclidean distance.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] Using this technique each term in each vector is first divided by the magnitude of the vector, yielding a vector of unit length.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] Once the normalisation has occurred, the vector space can be used with the full range of techniques available to any Euclidean space, notably standard dimensionality reduction techniques.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] This normalised form distance is often used within many deep learning algorithms.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] Here, A and B are sets, and $|A|$ is the number of elements in A .
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] If sets are represented as bit vectors, the Otsuka–Ochiai coefficient can be seen to be the same as the cosine similarity.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] It is identical to the score introduced by Godfrey Thomson.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] In a recent book, the coefficient is tentatively misattributed to another Japanese researcher with the family name Otsuka.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] The confusion arises because in 1957 Akira Ochiai attributes the coefficient only to Otsuka (no first name mentioned) by citing an article by Ikuso Hamai (Japanese: 浜井 生三), who in turn cites the original 1936 article by Yanosuke Otsuka.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] The most noteworthy property of cosine similarity is that it reflects a relative, rather than absolute, comparison of the individual vector dimensions.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] For any positive constant a and vector V , the vectors V and $aV$ are maximally similar.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] The measure is thus most appropriate for data where frequency is more important than absolute values; notably, term frequency in documents.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] However more recent metrics with a grounding in information theory, such as Jensen–Shannon, SED, and triangular divergence have been shown to have improved semantics in at least some contexts.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity is related to Euclidean distance as follows.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] The Euclidean distance is called the *chord distance* (because it is the length of the chord on the unit circle) and it is the Euclidean distance between the vectors which were normalized to unit sum of squared values within them.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] This form of the triangle inequality can be used to bound the minimum and maximum similarity of two objects A and B if the similarities to a reference object C is already known.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] This is used for example in metric data indexing, but has also been used to accelerate spherical k-means clustering the same way the Euclidean triangle inequality has been used to accelerate regular k-means.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] A soft cosine or ("soft" similarity) between two vectors considers similarities between pairs of features.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] For example, in the field of natural language processing (NLP) the similarity among features is quite intuitive.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] Features such as words, *n*-grams, or syntactic *n*-grams can be quite similar, though formally they are considered as different features in the VSM.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] For example, words "play" and "game" are different words and thus mapped to different points in VSM; yet they are semantically related.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] In case of *n*-grams or syntactic *n*-grams, Levenshtein distance can be applied (in fact, Levenshtein distance can be applied to words as well).
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] For calculating soft cosine, the matrix **s** is used to indicate similarity between features.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] It can be calculated through Levenshtein distance, WordNet similarity, or other similarity measures.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] where *sij* = similarity(feature*i*, feature*j*).
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] If there is no similarity between features (*sii* = 1, *sij* = 0 for *i* ≠ *j*), the given equation is equivalent to the conventional cosine similarity formula.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] The time complexity of this measure is quadratic, which makes it applicable to real-world tasks.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] Note that the complexity can be reduced to subquadratic.
[src:recommender-systems/cosine-similarity] An efficient implementation of such soft cosine similarity is included in the Gensim open source library.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] Methods are commonly divided into linear and nonlinear approaches.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] Linear approaches can be further divided into feature selection and feature extraction.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] Dimensionality reduction can be used for noise reduction, data visualization, cluster analysis, or as an intermediate step to facilitate other analyses.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] The process of feature selection aims to find a suitable subset of the input variables (*features*, or *attributes*) for the task at hand.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] The three strategies are: the *filter* strategy (e.g., information gain), the *wrapper* strategy (e.g., accuracy-guided search), and the *embedded* strategy (features are added or removed while building the model based on prediction errors).
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] Data analysis such as regression or classification can be done in the reduced space more accurately than in the original space.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] Feature projection (also called feature extraction) transforms the data from the high-dimensional space to a space of fewer dimensions.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] The data transformation may be linear, as in principal component analysis (PCA), but many nonlinear dimensionality reduction techniques also exist.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] For multidimensional data, tensor representation can be used in dimensionality reduction through multilinear subspace learning.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] The main linear technique for dimensionality reduction, principal component analysis, performs a linear mapping of the data to a lower-dimensional space in such a way that the variance of the data in the low-dimensional representation is maximized.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] In practice, the covariance (and sometimes the correlation) matrix of the data is constructed and the eigenvectors on this matrix are computed.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] The eigenvectors that correspond to the largest eigenvalues (the principal components) can now be used to reconstruct a large fraction of the variance of the original data.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] Moreover, the first few eigenvectors can often be interpreted in terms of the large-scale physical behavior of the system, because they often contribute the vast majority of the system's energy, especially in low-dimensional systems.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] Still, this must be proved on a case-by-case basis as not all systems exhibit this behavior.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] The original space (with dimension of the number of points) has been reduced (with data loss, but hopefully retaining the most important variance) to the space spanned by a few eigenvectors.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] NMF decomposes a non-negative matrix to the product of two non-negative ones, which has been a promising tool in fields where only non-negative signals exist, such as astronomy.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] With a stable component basis during construction, and a linear modeling process, sequential NMF is able to preserve the flux in direct imaging of circumstellar structures in astronomy, as one of the methods of detecting exoplanets, especially for the direct imaging of circumstellar discs.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] In comparison with PCA, NMF does not remove the mean of the matrices, which leads to physical non-negative fluxes; therefore NMF is able to preserve more information than PCA as demonstrated by Ren et al.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] Principal component analysis can be employed in a nonlinear way by means of the kernel trick.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is capable of constructing nonlinear mappings that maximize the variance in the data.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is called kernel PCA.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] Other prominent nonlinear techniques include manifold learning techniques such as Isomap, locally linear embedding (LLE), Hessian LLE, Laplacian eigenmaps, and methods based on tangent space analysis.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] More recently, techniques have been proposed that, instead of defining a fixed kernel, try to learn the kernel using semidefinite programming.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] The most prominent example of such a technique is maximum variance unfolding (MVU).
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] The central idea of MVU is to exactly preserve all pairwise distances between nearest neighbors (in the inner product space) while maximizing the distances between points that are not nearest neighbors.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] An alternative approach to neighborhood preservation is through the minimization of a cost function that measures differences between distances in the input and output spaces.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] A different approach to nonlinear dimensionality reduction is through the use of autoencoders, a special kind of feedforward neural networks with a bottleneck hidden layer.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] The training of deep encoders is typically performed using a greedy layer-wise pre-training (e.g., using a stack of restricted Boltzmann machines) that is followed by a finetuning stage based on backpropagation.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) is a generalization of Fisher's linear discriminant, a method used in statistics, pattern recognition, and machine learning to find a linear combination of features that characterizes or separates two or more classes of objects or events.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] GDA deals with nonlinear discriminant analysis using kernel function operator.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] The underlying theory is close to the support-vector machines (SVM) insofar as the GDA method provides a mapping of the input vectors into high-dimensional feature space.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] Similar to LDA, the objective of GDA is to find a projection for the features into a lower dimensional space by maximizing the ratio of between-class scatter to within-class scatter.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] Autoencoders can be used to learn nonlinear dimension reduction functions and codings together with an inverse function from the coding to the original representation.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] T-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique useful for the visualization of high-dimensional datasets.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] It is not recommended for use in analysis such as clustering or outlier detection since it does not necessarily preserve densities or distances well.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] Uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] Visually, it is similar to t-SNE, but it assumes that the data is uniformly distributed on a locally connected Riemannian manifold and that the Riemannian metric is locally constant or approximately locally constant.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] For high-dimensional datasets, dimension reduction is usually performed prior to applying a *k*-nearest neighbors (*k*-NN) algorithm in order to mitigate the curse of dimensionality.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] In machine learning, this process is also called low-dimensional embedding.
[src:recommender-systems/dimensionality-reduction] A dimensionality reduction technique that is sometimes used in neuroscience is maximally informative dimensions, which finds a lower-dimensional representation of a dataset such that as much information as possible about the original data is preserved.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] The idea behind matrix factorization is to represent users and items in a lower dimensional latent space.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Since the initial work by Funk in 2006 a multitude of matrix factorization approaches have been proposed for recommender systems.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Some of the most used and simpler ones are listed in the following sections.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] The original algorithm proposed by Simon Funk in his blog post factorized the user-item rating matrix as the product of two lower dimensional matrices, the first one has a row for each user, while the second has a column for each item.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] The row or column associated to a specific user or item is referred to as *latent factors*.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Note that, in Funk MF no singular value decomposition is applied, it is a SVD-like machine learning model.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] It is possible to tune the expressive power of the model by changing the number of latent factors.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] It has been demonstrated that a matrix factorization with one latent factor is equivalent to a *most popular* or *top popular* recommender (e.g. recommends the items with the most interactions without any personalization).
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Increasing the number of latent factors will improve personalization, therefore recommendation quality, until the number of factors becomes too high, at which point the model starts to overfit and the recommendation quality will decrease.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] A common strategy to avoid overfitting is to add regularization terms to the objective function.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Funk MF was developed as a *rating prediction* problem, therefore it uses explicit numerical ratings as user-item interactions.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Where $\|.\|_{\rm {F}}$ is defined to be the frobenius norm whereas the other norms might be either frobenius or another norm depending on the specific recommending problem.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] While Funk MF is able to provide very good recommendation quality, its ability to use only explicit numerical ratings as user-items interactions constitutes a limitation.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Modern day recommender systems should exploit all available interactions both explicit (e.g. numerical ratings) and implicit (e.g. likes, purchases, skipped, bookmarked).
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] To this end SVD++ was designed to take into account implicit interactions as well.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Compared to Funk MF, SVD++ takes also into account user and item bias.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Where $\mu$ refers to the overall average rating over all items and $b_{i}$ and $b_{u}$ refers to the observed deviation of the item i and the user u respectively from the average.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] SVD++ has however some disadvantages, with the main drawback being that this method is not *model-based.* This means that if a new user is added, the algorithm is incapable of modeling it unless the whole model is retrained.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Even though the system might have gathered some interactions for that new user, its latent factors are not available and therefore no recommendations can be computed.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] This is an example of a cold-start problem, that is the recommender cannot deal efficiently with new users or items and specific strategies should be put in place to handle this disadvantage.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] A possible way to address this cold start problem is to modify SVD++ in order for it to become a *model-based* algorithm, therefore allowing to easily manage new items and new users.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] As previously mentioned in SVD++ we don't have the latent factors of new users, therefore it is necessary to represent them in a different way.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] The user's latent factors represent the preference of that user for the corresponding item's latent factors, therefore user's latent factors can be estimated via the past user interactions.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] If the system is able to gather some interactions for the new user it is possible to estimate its latent factors.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Note that this does not entirely solve the cold-start problem, since the recommender still requires some reliable interactions for new users, but at least there is no need to recompute the whole model every time.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] It has been demonstrated that this formulation is almost equivalent to a SLIM model, which is an item-item model based recommender.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] With this formulation, the equivalent item-item recommender would be ${\tilde {R}}=RS=RW^{\rm {T}}W$ .
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Therefore the similarity matrix is symmetric.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Asymmetric SVD aims at combining the advantages of SVD++ while being a model based algorithm, therefore being able to consider new users with a few ratings without needing to retrain the whole model.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] As opposed to the model-based SVD here the user latent factor matrix H is replaced by Q, which learns the user's preferences as function of their ratings.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] With this formulation, the equivalent item-item recommender would be ${\tilde {R}}=RS=RQ^{\rm {T}}W$ .
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Since matrices Q and W are different the similarity matrix is asymmetric, hence the name of the model.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] A group-specific SVD can be an effective approach for the cold-start problem in many scenarios.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] It clusters users and items based on dependency information and similarities in characteristics.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Then once a new user or item arrives, we can assign a group label to it, and approximates its latent factor by the group effects (of the corresponding group).
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Therefore, although ratings associated with the new user or item are not necessarily available, the group effects provide immediate and effective predictions.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Here $v_{u}$ and $j_{i}$ represent the group label of user *u* and item *i*, respectively, which are identical across members from the same group.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] And S and T are matrices of group effects.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] This provides a good approximation to the unobserved ratings.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] In recent years many other matrix factorization models have been developed to exploit the ever increasing amount and variety of available interaction data and use cases.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] In recent years a number of neural and deep-learning techniques have been proposed, some of which generalize traditional Matrix factorization algorithms via a non-linear neural architecture.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] While deep learning has been applied to many different scenarios (context-aware, sequence-aware, social tagging, etc.), its real effectiveness when used in a simple Collaborative filtering scenario has been put into question.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Systematic analysis of publications applying deep learning or neural methods to the top-k recommendation problem, published in top conferences (SIGIR, KDD, WWW, RecSys, IJCAI), has shown that on average less than 40% of articles are reproducible, with as little as 14% in some conferences.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Overall the studies identify 26 articles, only 12 of them could be reproduced and 11 of them could be outperformed by much older and simpler properly tuned baselines.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] The articles also highlights a number of potential problems in today's research scholarship and call for improved scientific practices in that area.
[src:recommender-systems/matrix-factorization-recommender-systems] Similar issues have been spotted also in sequence-aware recommender systems.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] A **recommender system**, also called a **recommendation algorithm**, **recommendation engine**, **recommendation platform**, or in the context of social media, simply **algorithm** is a type of information filtering system that suggests items most relevant to a particular user.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The value of these systems becomes particularly evident in scenarios where users must select from a large number of options, such as products, media, or content.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Major social media platforms and streaming services rely on recommender systems that employ machine learning to analyze user behavior and preferences, thereby enabling personalized content feeds.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Typically, the suggestions refer to a variety of decision-making processes, including the selection of a product, musical selection, or online news source to read.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] These systems can operate using a single type of input, such as music, or multiple inputs from diverse platforms, including news, books and search queries.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Additionally, popular recommender systems have been developed for specific topics, such as restaurants and online dating services.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Recommender systems have also been developed to explore research articles and experts, collaborators, and financial services.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] A **content discovery platform** is a software recommendation platform that employs recommender system tools.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] It utilizes user metadata in order to identify and suggest relevant content, whilst reducing ongoing maintenance and development costs.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] A content discovery platform delivers personalized content to websites, mobile devices, and set-top boxes.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] A large range of content discovery platforms currently exist for various forms of content ranging from news articles and academic journal articles to television.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] As operators compete to serve as the gateway to home entertainment, personalized television emerges as a key service differentiator.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Academic content discovery has recently become another area of interest, the emergence of numerous companies dedicated to assisting academic researchers in keeping up to date with relevant academic content and facilitating serendipitous discovery of new content.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Recommender systems usually make use of either or both collaborative filtering and content-based filtering, as well as other systems such as knowledge-based systems.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Collaborative filtering approaches build a model from a user's past behavior (e.g., items previously purchased or selected and/or numerical ratings given to those items) as well as similar decisions made by other users.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] This model is then used to predict items (or ratings for items) that the user may have an interest in.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Content-based filtering approaches utilize a series of discrete, pre-tagged characteristics of an item in order to recommend additional items with similar properties.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The differences between collaborative and content-based filtering can be demonstrated by comparing two early music recommender systems, Last.fm and Pandora Radio.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Each type of system has its strengths and weaknesses.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] In the above example, Last.fm requires a large amount of information about a user to make accurate recommendations.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] This is an example of the cold start problem, and is common in collaborative filtering systems.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Whereas Pandora needs very little information to start, it is far more limited in scope (for example, it can only make recommendations that are similar to the original seed).
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Recommender systems are a useful alternative to search algorithms since they help users discover items they might not have found otherwise.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Of note, recommender systems are often implemented using search engines indexing non-traditional data.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Google Supreme Court case, may argue that search and recommendation algorithms are different technologies.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Recommender systems have been the focus of several granted patents, and there are more than 50 software libraries that support the development of recommender systems including LensKit, RecBole, ReChorus and RecPack.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Elaine Rich created the first recommender system in 1979, called Grundy.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] She looked for a way to recommend users books they might like.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Her idea was to create a system that asks users specific questions and classifies them into classes of preferences, or "stereotypes", depending on their answers.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Depending on users' stereotype membership, they would then get recommendations for books they might like.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Montaner provided the first overview of recommender systems from an intelligent agent perspective.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Gediminas Adomavicius provided a new, alternate overview of recommender systems.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Herlocker provides an additional overview of evaluation techniques for recommender systems, and Beel et al. discussed the problems of offline evaluations.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Beel et al. have also provided literature surveys on available research paper recommender systems and existing challenges.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] An example of predicting of the user's rating using collaborative filtering.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] One approach to the design of recommender systems that has wide use is collaborative filtering.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Collaborative filtering is based on the assumption that people who agreed in the past will agree in the future, and that they will like similar kinds of items as they liked in the past.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The system generates recommendations using only information about rating profiles for different users or items.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] By locating peer users/items with a rating history similar to the current user or item, they generate recommendations using this neighborhood.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The collaborative filtering approach does not rely on machine analyzable content and therefore it is capable of accurately recommending complex items such as movies without requiring an "understanding" of the item itself.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Many algorithms have been used in measuring user similarity or item similarity in recommender systems.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] For example, the k-nearest neighbor (k-NN) approach and the Pearson Correlation as first implemented by Allen.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Collaborative filtering approaches often suffer from three problems: cold start, scalability, and sparsity.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Social networking services have used collaborative filtering to recommend new friends, groups, and other social connections by examining the network of connections between a user and their friends.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Another common approach when designing recommender systems is **content-based filtering**.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Content-based filtering methods are based on a description of the item and a profile of the user's preferences.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] These methods are best suited to situations where there is known data on an item (name, location, description, etc.), but not on the user.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Content-based recommenders treat recommendation as a user-specific classification problem and learn a classifier for the user's likes and dislikes based on an item's features.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] In this system, keywords are used to describe the items, and a user profile is built to indicate the type of item this user likes.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] In other words, these algorithms try to recommend items similar to those that a user liked in the past or is examining in the present.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] It does not rely on a user sign-in mechanism to generate this often temporary profile.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] In particular, various candidate items are compared with items previously rated by the user, and the best-matching items are recommended.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] This approach has its roots in information retrieval and information filtering research.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] A history of the user's interaction with the recommender system.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Basically, these methods use an item profile (i.e., a set of discrete attributes and features) characterizing the item within the system.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] To abstract the features of the items in the system, an item presentation algorithm is applied.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] A widely used algorithm is the tf–idf representation (also called vector space representation).
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The system creates a content-based profile of users based on a weighted vector of item features.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The weights denote the importance of each feature to the user and can be computed from individually rated content vectors using a variety of techniques.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] A key issue with content-based filtering is whether the system can learn user preferences from users' actions regarding one content source and use them across other content types.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] When the system is limited to recommending content of the same type as the user is already using, the value from the recommendation system is significantly less than when other content types from other services can be recommended.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] For example, recommending news articles based on news browsing is useful.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Still, it would be much more useful when music, videos, products, discussions, etc., from different services, can be recommended based on news browsing.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] To overcome this, most content-based recommender systems now use some form of the hybrid system.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Content-based recommender systems can also include opinion-based recommender systems.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] In some cases, users are allowed to leave text reviews or feedback on the items.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] These user-generated texts are implicit data for the recommender system because they are potentially rich resources of both feature/aspects of the item and users' evaluation/sentiment to the item.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Features extracted from the user-generated reviews are improved metadata of items, because as they also reflect aspects of the item like metadata, extracted features are widely concerned by the users.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Sentiments extracted from the reviews can be seen as users' rating scores on the corresponding features.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Popular approaches of opinion-based recommender system utilize various techniques including text mining, information retrieval, sentiment analysis (see also Multimodal sentiment analysis) and deep learning.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Most recommender systems now use a hybrid approach, combining collaborative filtering, content-based filtering, and other approaches.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Hybrid approaches can be implemented in several ways: by making content-based and collaborative-based predictions separately and then combining them; by adding content-based capabilities to a collaborative-based approach (and vice versa); or by unifying the approaches into one model.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Several studies that empirically compared the performance of the hybrid with the pure collaborative and content-based methods and demonstrated that the hybrid methods can provide more accurate recommendations than pure approaches.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] These methods can also be used to overcome some of the common problems in recommender systems such as cold start and the sparsity problem, as well as the knowledge engineering bottleneck in knowledge-based approaches.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Netflix uses a hybrid recommender systems to make recommendations by comparing the watching and searching habits of similar users (i.e., collaborative filtering) as well as by offering movies that share characteristics with films that a user has rated highly (content-based filtering).
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] These recommender systems use the interactions of a user within a session to generate recommendations.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Session-based recommender systems are used at YouTube and Amazon.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] These are particularly useful when history (such as past clicks, purchases) of a user is not available or not relevant in the current user session.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Domains where session-based recommendations are particularly relevant include video, e-commerce, travel, music and more.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Most instances of session-based recommender systems rely on the sequence of recent interactions within a session without requiring any additional details (historical, demographic) of the user.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Techniques for session-based recommendations are mainly based on generative sequential models such as recurrent neural networks, transformers, and other deep-learning-based approaches.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The recommendation problem can be seen as a special instance of a reinforcement learning problem whereby the user is the environment upon which the agent, the recommendation system acts upon in order to receive a reward, for instance, a click or engagement by the user.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] One aspect of reinforcement learning that is of particular use in the area of recommender systems is the fact that the models or policies can be learned by providing a reward to the recommendation agent.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] This is in contrast to traditional learning techniques which rely on supervised learning approaches that are less flexible, reinforcement learning recommendation techniques allow to potentially train models that can be optimized directly on metrics of engagement, and user interest.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Multi-criteria recommender systems (MCRS) can be defined as recommender systems that incorporate preference information upon multiple criteria.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Instead of developing recommendation techniques based on a single criterion value, the overall preference of user u for the item i, these systems try to predict a rating for unexplored items of u by exploiting preference information on multiple criteria that affect this overall preference value.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Several researchers approach MCRS as a multi-criteria decision making (MCDM) problem, and apply MCDM methods and techniques to implement MCRS systems.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] See this chapter for an extended introduction.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The majority of existing approaches to recommender systems focus on recommending the most relevant content to users using contextual information, yet do not take into account the risk of disturbing the user with unwanted notifications.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] It is important to consider the risk of upsetting the user by pushing recommendations in certain circumstances, for instance, during a professional meeting, early morning, or late at night.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Therefore, the performance of the recommender system depends in part on the degree to which it has incorporated the risk into the recommendation process.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] One option to manage this issue is *DRARS*, a system which models the context-aware recommendation as a bandit problem.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] This system combines a content-based technique and a contextual bandit algorithm.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Mobile recommender systems make use of internet-accessing smartphones to offer personalized, context-sensitive recommendations.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] This is a particularly difficult area of research as mobile data is more complex than data that recommender systems often have to deal with.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] It is heterogeneous, noisy, requires spatial and temporal auto-correlation, and has validation and generality problems.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] There are three factors that could affect the mobile recommender systems and the accuracy of prediction results: the context, the recommendation method and privacy.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Additionally, mobile recommender systems suffer from a transplantation problem – recommendations may not apply in all regions (for instance, it would be unwise to recommend a recipe in an area where all of the ingredients may not be available).
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] One example of a mobile recommender system are the approaches taken by companies such as Uber and Lyft to generate driving routes for taxi drivers in a city.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] This system uses GPS data of the routes that taxi drivers take while working, which includes location (latitude and longitude), time stamps, and operational status (with or without passengers).
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] It uses this data to recommend a list of pickup points along a route, with the goal of optimizing occupancy times and profits.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Generative recommenders (GR) represent an approach that transforms recommendation tasks into sequential transduction problems, where user actions are treated like tokens in a generative modeling framework.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] By turning all of the system’s varied data into a single stream of tokens and using a custom self-attention approach instead of traditional neural network layers, generative recommenders make the model much simpler and less memory-hungry.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] As a result, it can improve recommendation quality in test simulations and in real-world tests, while being faster than previous Transformer-based systems when handling long lists of user actions.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Ultimately, this approach allows the model’s performance to grow steadily as more computing power is used, laying a foundation for efficient and scalable “foundation models” for recommendations.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] One of the events that energized research in recommender systems was the Netflix Prize.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] From 2006 to 2009, Netflix sponsored a competition, offering a grand prize of $1,000,000 to the team that could take an offered dataset of over 100 million movie ratings and return recommendations that were 10% more accurate than those offered by the company's existing recommender system.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] This competition energized the search for new and more accurate algorithms.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] On 21 September 2009, the grand prize of US$1,000,000 was given to the BellKor's Pragmatic Chaos team using tiebreaking rules.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The most accurate algorithm in 2007 used an ensemble method of 107 different algorithmic approaches, blended into a single prediction.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Many benefits accrued to the web due to the Netflix project.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Some teams have taken their technology and applied it to other markets.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Some members from the team that finished second place founded Gravity R&D, a recommendation engine that's active in the RecSys community.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] 4-Tell, Inc. created a Netflix project–derived solution for ecommerce websites.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] A number of privacy issues arose around the dataset offered by Netflix for the Netflix Prize competition.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Although the data sets were anonymized in order to preserve customer privacy, in 2007 two researchers from the University of Texas were able to identify individual users by matching the data sets with film ratings on the Internet Movie Database (IMDb).
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] As a result, in December 2009, an anonymous Netflix user sued Netflix in Doe v.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Netflix, alleging that Netflix had violated United States fair trade laws and the Video Privacy Protection Act by releasing the datasets.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] This, as well as concerns from the Federal Trade Commission, led to the cancellation of a second Netflix Prize competition in 2010.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Evaluation is important in assessing the effectiveness of recommendation algorithms.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] To measure the effectiveness of recommender systems, and compare different approaches, three types of evaluations are available: user studies, online evaluations (A/B tests), and offline evaluations.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The commonly used metrics are the mean squared error and root mean squared error, the latter having been used in the Netflix Prize.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The information retrieval metrics such as precision and recall or discounted cumulative gain (DCG) are useful to assess the quality of a recommendation method.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Diversity, novelty, and coverage are also considered as important aspects in evaluation.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] However, many of the classic evaluation measures are highly criticized.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Evaluating the performance of a recommendation algorithm on a fixed test dataset will always be extremely challenging as it is impossible to accurately predict the reactions of real users to the recommendations.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Hence any metric that computes the effectiveness of an algorithm in offline data will be imprecise.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] A few dozens or hundreds of users are presented recommendations created by different recommendation approaches, and then the users judge which recommendations are best.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] In A/B tests, recommendations are shown to typically thousands of users of a real product, and the recommender system randomly picks at least two different recommendation approaches to generate recommendations.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The effectiveness is measured with implicit measures of effectiveness such as conversion rate or click-through rate.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Offline evaluations are based on historic data, e.g. a dataset that contains information about how users previously rated movies.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The effectiveness of recommendation approaches is then measured based on how well a recommendation approach can predict the users' ratings in the dataset.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] While a rating is an explicit expression of whether a user liked a movie, such information is not available in all domains.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] For instance, in the domain of citation recommender systems, users typically do not rate a citation or recommended article.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] In such cases, offline evaluations may use implicit measures of effectiveness.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] For instance, it may be assumed that a recommender system is effective that is able to recommend as many articles as possible that are contained in a research article's reference list.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] However, this kind of offline evaluations is seen critical by many researchers.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] For instance, it has been shown that results of offline evaluations have low correlation with results from user studies or A/B tests.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] A dataset popular for offline evaluation has been shown to contain duplicate data and thus to lead to wrong conclusions in the evaluation of algorithms.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Often, results of so-called offline evaluations do not correlate with actually assessed user-satisfaction.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] This is probably because offline training is highly biased toward the highly reachable items, and offline testing data is highly influenced by the outputs of the online recommendation module.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Researchers have concluded that the results of offline evaluations should be viewed critically.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Typically, research on recommender systems is concerned with finding the most accurate recommendation algorithms.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] However, there are a number of factors that are also important.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Recommender systems are notoriously difficult to evaluate offline, with some researchers claiming that this has led to a reproducibility crisis in recommender systems publications.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The topic of reproducibility seems to be a recurrent issue in some Machine Learning publication venues, but does not have a considerable effect beyond the world of scientific publication.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The articles considers a number of potential problems in today's research scholarship and suggests improved scientific practices in that area.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] More recent work on benchmarking a set of the same methods came to qualitatively very different results whereby neural methods were found to be among the best performing methods.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Deep learning and neural methods for recommender systems have been used in the winning solutions in several recent recommender system challenges, WSDM, RecSys Challenge.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Moreover, neural and deep learning methods are widely used in industry where they are extensively tested.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The topic of reproducibility is not new in recommender systems.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] By 2011, Ekstrand, Konstan, et al. criticized that "it is currently difficult to reproduce and extend recommender systems research results," and that evaluations are "not handled consistently".
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Hence, operators of recommender systems find little guidance in the current research for answering the question, which recommendation approaches to use in a recommender systems.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Said and Bellogín conducted a study of papers published in the field, as well as benchmarked some of the most popular frameworks for recommendation and found large inconsistencies in results, even when the same algorithms and data sets were used.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Some researchers demonstrated that minor variations in the recommendation algorithms or scenarios led to strong changes in the effectiveness of a recommender system.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Artificial intelligence (AI) applications in recommendation systems are the advanced methodologies that leverage AI technologies, to enhance the performance recommendation engines.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The AI-based recommender can analyze complex data sets, learning from user behavior, preferences, and interactions to generate highly accurate and personalized content or product suggestions.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The integration of AI in recommendation systems has marked a significant evolution from traditional recommendation methods.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Traditional methods often relied on inflexible algorithms that could suggest items based on general user trends or apparent similarities in content.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] In comparison, AI-powered systems have the capability to detect patterns and subtle distinctions that may be overlooked by traditional methods.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] These systems can adapt to specific individual preferences, thereby offering recommendations that are more aligned with individual user needs.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] This approach marks a shift towards more personalized, user-centric suggestions.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Recommendation systems widely adopt AI techniques such as machine learning, deep learning, and natural language processing.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] These advanced methods enhance system capabilities to predict user preferences and deliver personalized content more accurately.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The following sections will introduce specific AI models utilized by a recommendation system by illustrating their theories and functionalities.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Collaborative filtering (CF) is one of the most commonly used recommendation system algorithms.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] It generates personalized suggestions for users based on explicit or implicit behavioral patterns to form predictions.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Specifically, it relies on external feedback such as star ratings, purchasing history and so on to make judgments.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] CF make predictions about users' preference based on similarity measurements.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] There are many models available for collaborative filtering.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] For AI-applied collaborative filtering, a common model is called K-nearest neighbors.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] **Statistical Distance**: 'Distance' measures how far apart users are in this space.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] **Forming Predictive Recommendations**: The system will analyze the similar preference of the k neighbors.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] An artificial neural network (ANN), is a deep learning model structure which aims to mimic a human brain.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] They comprise a series of neurons, each responsible for receiving and processing information transmitted from other interconnected neurons.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Similar to a human brain, these neurons will change activation state based on incoming signals (training input and backpropagated output), allowing the system to adjust activation weights during the network learning phase.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] ANN is usually designed to be a black-box model.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Unlike regular machine learning where the underlying theoretical components are formal and rigid, the collaborative effects of neurons are not entirely clear, but modern experiments has shown the predictive power of ANN.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] ANN is widely used in recommendation systems for its power to utilize various data.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Other than feedback data, ANN can incorporate non-feedback data which are too intricate for collaborative filtering to learn, and the unique structure allows ANN to identify extra signal from non-feedback data to boost user experience.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The Two-Tower model is a neural architecture commonly employed in large-scale recommendation systems, particularly for candidate retrieval tasks.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The outputs of the two towers are fixed-length embeddings that represent users and items in a shared vector space.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] A similarity metric, such as dot product or cosine similarity, is used to measure relevance between a user and an item.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] This model is highly efficient for large datasets as embeddings can be pre-computed for items, allowing rapid retrieval during inference.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] It is often used in conjunction with ranking models for end-to-end recommendation pipelines.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Natural language processing is a series of AI algorithms to make natural human language accessible and analyzable to a machine.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] It is a fairly modern technique inspired by the growing amount of textual information.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] For application in recommendation system, a common case is the Amazon customer review.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Amazon will analyze the feedbacks comments from each customer and report relevant data to other customers for reference.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] The recent years have witnessed the development of various text analysis models, including latent semantic analysis (LSA), singular value decomposition (SVD), latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA), etc.
[src:recommender-systems/recommender-system] Their uses have consistently aimed to provide customers with more precise and tailored recommendations.
